title: First Amendment Trainings for Law-Enforcement Officers (Denver Police Department)

communications.subject: Colorado Open Records Act Request: First Amendment Trainings for Law-Enforcement Officers (Denver Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Colorado Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. Any materials or programming (including handouts, slideshows, videos, textbooks, or other media) used in connection with providing training or guidance to law-enforcement officers in your agency with respect to any of the following subjects: (a) The First Amendment; (b) protests or demonstrations; (c) freedom of speech or expression; (d) filming police officers. This request is limited to materials used in trainings since January 1, 2020.

2. Any policy concerning whether trainings on the topics mentioned in (1) are mandatory, or regulating the frequency of such trainings.

3. A copy of any document sufficient to show the most recent training conducted for law-enforcement officers in your agency with respect to any of the subjects in (1). For example, this could be a receipt or contract for an outside vendor or speaker, or it could be a dated sign-in sheet from the training.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Diplomatic Intercepts - Romania
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of FBI file 65-HQ-57411, on the interception of diplomatic communications from the Romanian government during World War II.

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies. If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Galante

you receive a comment that your FOIPA request number was not located in the
database, please check back at a later date.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1433170-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@ic.fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 138 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 571 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,289 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 1,649 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
Record/Information Dissemination Section (RIDS) FBI-Information Management Division
170 Marcel Drive, Winchester, VA 22602-4843
Direct: (540) 868-4593
Fax: (540) 868-4391
Questions E-mail: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1433170-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 106 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 785 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,695 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,088 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
170 Marcel Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
F: (540) 868-4391
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: FOIA# 1433170-000/ 065-HQ-57411
communications.communication:
Good afternoon Mr. Galante,

This is in reference to your FOIPA request # 1433170-000 for FBI records concerning 065-HQ-57411. We are reaching out to you to determine if you are still interested in these records, or, if at this time, you would consider reducing the size of your request.

Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system, and the FBI receives a voluminous amount of requests on a daily, weekly, monthly, and annual basis. Requests are divided into two primary tracks -simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents). Complex requests are further divided into medium (51-500 pages), large (501-4,999 pages), and extra-large (5,000 and over pages) sub-tracks are based upon request size.

Your request is currently in the large track and reducing the scope of your request may accelerate the processing, allow for a timelier receipt of the information you seek, and reduce the duplication costs, if applicable.

Please contact us with regards to this inquiry to let us know if you are still interested in receiving records for this request either in full (the remaining records), or reducing the request to a faster processing track.
If you reduce the size, you may request remaining, additional records by submitting a new FOIPA request upon completion of this one.

Respectfully,

Negotiation Team
Federal Bureau of Investigation
Fbi.foipa.negotiation@fbi.gov<mailto:Fbi.foipa.negotiation@fbi.gov>

Status Checks: https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps | foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>
For additional information, please visit the www.fbi.gov/foia<http://www.fbi.gov/foia> website.

communications.subject: Colorado Open Records Act Request: Flock Safety Devices List (Loveland CO Police Department}
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Colorado Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the department’s Flock Safety system:

Flock networks shared with me Devices List (Please see https://cdn.muckrock.com/foia_files/2022/11/17/CPRA_REQUEST.pdf
https://cdn.muckrock.com/foia_files/2022/11/09/1938_001.pdf as examples of the lists from other jurisdictions.

Please provide records in their original electronic, machine readable format. For example, please provide csv or spreadsheet files where applicable. Please do not redirect me to your transparency portal.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Tepper

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Swatting Documents
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

- Documents, memos, presentations, and emails (including attachments) written between January 1, 2020 and the date this request is processed regarding a spree of false reports of active shooting incidents called into schools and universities. A keyword search could include the words "hoax", "hoax call", "swatting", "false report" AND the words "school" or "university"

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Dhruv Mehrotra

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #2023-IAFO-00282
communications.communication:
You have reached SecureRelease™ Support.

The purpose of this inbox is to provide technical support for the SecureRelease FOIA Request Portal website (https://www.securerelease.us/).



SecureRelease Support is not involved with the processing or prioritization of FOIA requests, and our staff cannot answer questions related to request status, expected timelines, or agency procedures. To ask for an update or discuss the specifics of your request(s), you must contact the agency directly.


If you submitted your request(s) through the SecureRelease™ Request Portal<https://www.securerelease.us/> or to a participating agency using FOIA.gov, you may use SecureRelease Portal Messages to send electronic correspondence and attachments directly to the agency.



To send a portal message:



  1.  Sign in to the SecureRelease™ Request Portal: https://www.securerelease.us/account-page/sign-in/
  2.  Click the My Requests icon
  3.  Locate the request you wish to inquire about, and click on the Request Number
  4.  From the request screen, click the Messages icon at the top of the page
  5.  Click the Add Message button at the upper right
  6.  Complete the required Message Fields
  7.  Drag and drop any Files you wish to attach into the file upload box (Optional)
     *   Maximum of 25 files can be attached to a message, and total file size cannot be more than 100 mb. Supported file formats: DOC, DOCX, XLS, XLSX, TXT, PDF, JPG, PNG, BMP and TIF/TIFF
  8.  Click Send
  9.  Return to the Messages tab within your Request to access outgoing and incoming messages


Should you have an inquiry related to your SecureRelease user account or concerning www.securerelease.us<http://www.securerelease.us>, please email us with the relevant details and a member of our support team will be happy to assist.



Take care,


SecureRelease™ Support Team
securereleasesupportteam@deloitte.com<mailto:securereleasesupportteam@deloitte.com>
www.securerelease.us<https://www.securerelease.us/>

title: Library contract request: EBSCO eBooks at Wright State University

communications.subject: Ohio Open Records Law Request: Library contract request: EBSCO eBooks at Wright State University
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Ohio Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

The most recent contract, governing, base, or master license agreement with EBSCO Information Services (EBSCO Industries, Inc. "EBSCO") relating to the licensing of EBSCO eBooks;

All related terms and conditions, terms of service, amendments, addenda, appendices, attachments, product terms, MOUs, MOAs, data processing agreements, and/or letters of intent; and

All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to the contractual relations with EBSCO for e-book licensing. 

Responsive materials include all contracts, agreements, amendments, appendices, invoices, and any other documents listed above that incorporate language governing terms of use of EBSCO eBooks.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

smhc

title:
Anthony Provenzale FOIA Request
Legal Secretary Position

communications.subject: Connecticut Freedom of Information Act Request: Untitled
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Connecticut Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

City of Danbury CT Human Resources All applicant data related to the open position of legal secretary from 8/1/24 until 12//18/24. All information pertaining to applicant sex, race, creed and national origin. Any and all information concerning whom of anyone was hired Any and all information concerning any restructuring, including but not limited to eliminating the position of legal secretary. Any and all information concerning applicant Anthony Provenzale, for the position of legal secretary. Any and all information concerning interview notes, information, or details about Anthony Provenzale. Any and all information concerning Anthony Provenzale rank in the city of Danbury list of hiring for the position of legal secretary.

I also request that, if possible and pursuant to Conn. Gen. Stat. § 1-212(d), fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest and not made for commercial gain. The requested documents will be made available to the public at MuckRock.com.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 4 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Anthony Provenzale

title: Request for Public Records Request Log

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Request for Public Records Request Log
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I request a copy of any logs, spreadsheets, or databases maintained by your office that track public records requests received, including (if available):

Date of request
Requester name
Summary or description of request
Response date
Disposition (granted, denied, etc.)
Fee charged, if any

If available, please provide the data in spreadsheet or machine-readable format (e.g., CSV or Excel).

Please provide 2024 and 2025.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brian McCarter

Please be advised that in the case of a denial of access to records, you have the right to an administrative appeal to the Supervisor of Records, pursuant to 950 CMR 32.08(1) (the Code of Massachusetts Regulations), and the right to seek judicial review by commencing an action in the Superior Court.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Martin Theodore Orne
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning, relating to, or generated as a resulf of investigation or inquiry of Martin Theodore Orne (October 16, 1927 - February 11, 2000). Proof of death is not required as his death was widely reported: https://www.nytimes.com/2000/02/17/us/martin-orne-72-psychiatrist-and-expert-on-hypnosis-dies.html

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies. This is also to include any responsive records held in offsite locations, such as the Alexandria Records Center. Please include both investigatory and non-investigatory records in your search. If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Galante

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Ohio Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to the [State] Public Records Act, I request copies of police reports for all traffic stops conducted by the [Police Department] between August 1, 2025 and August 7, 2025 that resulted in an arrest. If no arrest please widen search from August 1, 2025 and August 31, 2025.

If the department cannot search by stop type, please instead provide:

The arrest log for the same dates; and The corresponding incident or arrest reports for those arrests that originated from a traffic stop.

Please provide these records in electronic format of PDF or Word/Excel. If any portion of the requested records is exempt from disclosure, please redact only the exempt material and release all reasonably segregable portions of the record.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Rights React

Good Morning,

See attached list of arrests related to your request. Going through each call and getting the report & redacting etc takes some time, so please let me know if you are interested in receiving specific report(s) for any of the listed call number.  

**Please respond via email to: police/clerks@whitehall-oh.us

Thank you,

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Banned books list (Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

A list of all books and other printed publications that are banned or otherwise not permitted in prisons. Please include the title and author of the publication. If available, please include the reasons for prohibiting the publication, as well as the date of the decision.

If possible, please send this information in a searchable spreadsheet format, such as an Excel file or a CSV file.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Dillon Bergin

communications.subject: Connecticut Freedom of Information Act Request: BOE Contact Form Submissions
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Connecticut Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Copies of all submissions made through the Board of Education website contact form during the period from July 1, 2024 through the date of this request.

I understand that some submissions may contain information exempt from disclosure (e.g., student education records protected by under state/federal law, or personally identifying information). I respectfully request that any such information be redacted as necessary, rather than withholding the entire record.

I also request that, if possible and pursuant to Conn. Gen. Stat. § 1-212(d), fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest and not made for commercial gain. The requested documents will be made available to the public at MuckRock.com.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 4 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Sam Bellford

communications.subject: Re: Connecticut Freedom of Information Act Request: BOE Contact Form Submissions
communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Bellford,

On behalf of the Thomaston Board of Education, I am writing to inform you
that the review of your request is completed. Please note that while
responsive records have been located, certain information is required by
law to be withheld. Specifically, the Connecticut Freedom of Information
Act and federal student privacy laws (including FERPA) mandate the
protection of personally identifiable information related to students, as
well as certain personal data related to staff. For this reason, redactions
were applied prior to release.

Additionally, the format in which the submissions are stored does not lend
itself to clean printing. The records have nonetheless been preserved in
their original form, with only the necessary redactions made to protect
students and staff.

We trust this clarifies the basis for the formatting and redaction in the
materials provided.

Sincerely,
Francine Coss

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Untitled (Department of Justice, Office of the Attorney General)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Greetings. I request copies of any memos, studies, or other such records dated Jan 1, 2020, through the date you complete your search, referencing (1) the Justice Department resources spent or expected to be spent litigating Freedom of Information Act cases or (2) the frequency with which the government has won or lost Freedom of Information Act cases.  I'm not looking for individual emails that happen to make mention of these subjects, but rather, more formal studies or other such records that are the results of a more formal evaluation.  I'm happy to discuss the scope with you.  By "resources" I mean the costs in terms of attorney/staff hours, FTEs, or salaries.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Topic

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Mayday USA Tour (Seattle Office Of Special Events)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

I am writing in regards to a pair of public demonstrations and protests which occurred in Seattle last week. 
The first event was held in Cal Anderson Park on Saturday, May 24th. A second, followup event was held outside of City Hall on Tuesday, May 27th.
For the purposes of identifying the correct party and records, the event's original registration page can be found here: https://www.maydayusa.co/

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

* Permits and related application materials submitted to (or issued by) your department, including any attachments, maps, or forms, for either of the above events. 
     * If multiple venues were considered, I would like the relevant records for each of them.

* All correspondence (including emails, letters, and internal memos) between:
     * Your department and the organizers or any representatives of these events.
     * Your department and any other city department, specifically in regards to these events.
     * Internal communications within your department that relate to the planning, permitting, or management of these events.

Please include any records dated between January 1st, 2025, and June 1st, 2025.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Elizabeth Haste

communications.subject: City of Seattle Public Records Request Center - Invoice Ready :: C228486-060825
communications.communication:
Dear Elizabeth Haste, 
 
Records in response to your public disclosure request C228486-060825 received on June 08, 2025 are now available. The cost for the records is as follows: 
 
Invoice Number: INV25-C228486-1 
Total: $1.25 
 
To pay online, please follow these steps: 
 Please note that you will need to disable any pop-up blockers to make a payment using the system. 
 
  * Navigate to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * Select 'My Records Request Center'. 
  * Select 'View My Requests'. You may be asked to login. 
  * Find this request: C228486-060825. 
  * Select the 'View Invoices' button. 
 
  * Opens a pop-up window showing your invoice: INV25-C228486-1. 
  * Click on the invoice and then the 'Pay Now' button. 
  * Continue processing your payment. 
  * Select 'Done'. 
  * Once the payment process is done, you are returned to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * After your payment is successful you will receive an email from our payments center. 
Once your payment has been approved, we will send you an email with instructions on how to download your records. Note that City staff must manually upload records. Records will be available one to two business days after payment. 
 
Please let your public disclosure officer (PDO) know if you are unable to pay online; your PDO will work with you on alternative ways to make your payment. 
 
You have 30 days from today's date to pay for your records. If the City does not receive your payment within this time period, your request will be considered abandoned, and you will need to submit a new request.

The first event was held in Cal Anderson Park on Saturday, May 24th. A second, followup event was held outside of City Hall on Tuesday, May 27th. 
For the purposes of identifying the correct party and records, the event's original registration page can be found here: https://www.maydayusa.co/ 

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records: 

* Permits and related application materials submitted to (or issued by) your department, including any attachments, maps, or forms, for either of the above events. 
* If multiple venues were considered, I would like the relevant records for each of them. 

* All correspondence (including emails, letters, and internal memos) between: 
* Your department and the organizers or any representatives of these events. 
* Your department and any other city department, specifically in regards to these events. 
* Internal communications within your department that relate to the planning, permitting, or management of these events. 

Please include any records dated between January 1st, 2025, and June 1st, 2025. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Elizabeth Haste

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Beverage Agreements
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

Agreements related to the beverage pouring, distribution, sales or marketing rights for campus, athletics venues or facilities.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Kelly North

communications.subject: RE: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Beverage Agreements
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

I wanted to follow up on the following Illinois Freedom of Information Act. request, copied below, and originally submitted on Sept. 2, 2025. Please let me know when I can expect to receive a response.

Thanks for your help, and let me know if further clarification is needed.

communications.subject: FOIA Request 25-1386
communications.communication:
September 9, 2025

Via electronic mail
Kelly North
MuckRock
192384-70293303@requests.muckrock.com<mailto:192384-70293303@requests.muckrock.com>

Re: FOIA Request 25-1386

Dear Kelly North:

      I am responding to your request dated and received in my office September 2, 2025, under the Illinois Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) in which you requested:

      “…the following records:

Agreements related to the beverage pouring, distribution, sales or marketing rights for campus, athletics venues or facilities.”

      I am writing to invoke an extension of the deadline for responding to the request under the following section(s) of the FOIA, which allows for additional time when:


  *   140/3(e)(v) the requested records require examination and evaluation by personnel having the necessary competence and discretion to determine if they are exempt from disclosure under Section 7 of this Act or should be revealed only with appropriate deletions.

  *   140/3(e)(vi) the request for records cannot be complied with by the public body within the time limits prescribed by paragraph (c) of this Section without unduly burdening or interfering with the operations of the public body.


      We are taking the additional five business days allowed by law to complete processing this request. The revised deadline will now be September 16, 2025.

Sincerely,

Adrienne Nazon
Vice President, External Relations and Communications
and Chief Records Officer

communications.subject: FOIA Request 25-1386
communications.communication:
September 12, 2025

Via electronic mail
Kelly North
MuckRock
192384-70293303@requests.muckrock.com<mailto:192384-70293303@requests.muckrock.com>

Re: FOIA Request 25-1386

Dear Kelly North:

      I am responding to your request dated and received in my office September 2, 2025, under the Illinois Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) in which you requested from the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign:

      “…the following records:

Agreements related to the beverage pouring, distribution, sales or marketing rights for campus, athletics venues or facilities.”

      Information responsive to your request is available. These are public records numbering 108 pages. Due to file size, the records referenced above are available for download at  https://uofi.box.com/s/bdo5pjnoyv5dkx4pptsjhwkclwi5jh2w. This link will expire in 10 business days. Because reading files in the Box interface can be slow and challenging, we suggest that you click the Download button to save your responsive file to your device.

Portions of these records have been redacted pursuant to the following section(s) of the Act:


  *   140/7(1)(b) that exempts from disclosure “Private information, unless disclosure is required by another provision of this Act, a State or federal law or a court order.” This includes signatures and personal telephone numbers.



  *   140/7(1)(c) that exempts from disclosure “Personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which, if disclosed, would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subjects of the information.” This includes State Registration Certificate numbers.


      Please note: The contract for Coca-Cola with the is the most recent contract available, though it expired June 29, 2025. There is no other current, fully executed Coca-Cola contract available at this time.

      You have a right under the law to seek a review of this response by the Public Access Counselor (PAC) in the Office of the Attorney General. The PAC may be reached by phone at 877.299.3642 or by postal mail to Leah Bartelt, Public Access Counselor, Office of the Illinois Attorney General, 500 South 2nd Street, Springfield, Illinois 62701. You also have the right to seek judicial review under section 11 of this Act.

      If you have questions for our office, please contact 217-333-6400.

                                                                                                  Sincerely,

                                                                                                  Adrienne Nazon
                                                                                                  Vice President, External Relations and
                                                                                                  Communications
                                                                                                  and Chief Records Officer

title: Banned books list (Texas Department of Criminal Justice)

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Banned books list (Texas Department of Criminal Justice)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A list of all books and other printed publications that are banned or otherwise not permitted in prisons. Please include the title and author of the publication. If available, please include the reasons for prohibiting the publication, as well as the date of the decision.

If possible, please send this information in a searchable spreadsheet format, such as an Excel file or a CSV file.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Dillon Bergin

title: LAUSD, SDUSD, and Fresno USD CSSP 4.23.25 (Los Angeles Unified School District)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: LAUSD, SDUSD, and Fresno USD CSSP 4.23.25 (Los Angeles Unified School District)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All finalized Comprehensive School Safety Plans submitted from 2018 to present in a word or .pdf file. I would also like a compiled excel sheet of all the Comprehensive School Safety Plans on Section 32282 reporting, specifically Section (M)(i) regarding "Procedures to respond to incidents involving an individual experiencing a sudden cardiac arrest or a similar life-threatening medical emergency while on school grounds."

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Sejal Parekh

communications.subject: MuckRock #48 - 4.24.2025 - OGC Ctrl# 0101207
communications.communication:
The Office of the General Counsel received your above referenced California Public Records Act (PRA) Request, which seeks the records listed below.  After conducting a diligent inquiry and making a thorough search of our records, the District responds as follows:

  1.  All finalized Comprehensive School Safety Plans submitted from 2018 to present in a word or .pdf file.
                        Please note this Request demands the Los Angeles Unified School District, which has 1,543 schools, provide over 10,000 reports.  Consequently, the records requested have been determined to be exempt pursuant to the following authority:

·                     "A clearly framed request which requires an agency to search an enormous volume of data . . . . or, conversely, a request which compels the production of a huge volume of material may be objectionable as unduly burdensome." California First Amendment Coalition v. Superior Ct. (1998) 67 Cal. App.4th 159, 166; citing American Civil Liberties Union Foundation v. Deukmejian (1982) 32 Cal.3d 440, 186. "[C]ourts should not ignore any expense and inconvenience involved in segregating [information]." California First Amendment Coalition v. Superior Ct. (1998) 67 Cal. App. 4th 159, 1326.  A public agency is not to be subjected to an "onerous burden" when disclosing public records. ACLU v. Deukmejian (1982) 32 Cal.3d 440, 454.



·                     Records sought would be exempt pursuant to Government Code §7927.000, which states: "An agency shall justify withholding any record by demonstrating that the record in question is exempt under express provisions of this division, or that on the facts of the particular case the public interest served by not disclosing the record clearly outweighs the public interest served by disclosure of the record."  "The CPRA provides for more than two dozen specific exemptions, including a "catchall" exemption (§ 6255) (now 7922.000). . . . Thus, the Act is clear that the Legislature intended to restrict the public's access to some material."  Regents of University of California v. Superior Court (2013) 222 Cal. App. 4th 383, 400.



·                     Pursuant to California Government Code section 7922.540(b), Christopher Harris, J.D., Senior Paralegal, Office of the General Counsel, Public Records Act Unit, is the person responsible for the redactions or determinations.


  1.  I would also like a compiled excel sheet of all the Comprehensive School Safety Plans on Section 32282 reporting, specifically Section (M)(i) regarding "Procedures to respond to incidents involving an individual experiencing a sudden cardiac arrest or a similar life-threatening medical emergency while on school grounds."
The District previously responded to this Request in the First Rolling Production.

With the production of the above response, the District has completed this matter.
Thank you for contacting the Los Angeles Unified School District Public Records Act Unit.

communications.subject: Ohio Open Records Law Request: Consumer Complaints for Healthcare Prepayment (Ohio Dept of Insurance)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Ohio Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

an opportunity to inspect or obtain copies of public records of complaints to the Department of Financial Services regarding insurance and/or health care providers from 2015 to 2025 containing any of the phrases “prepay,” “upfront,” “down payment,” “refund,” or “reimbursed,” along with  “prior to necessary medical care,” and “non-emergency procedure.” This includes but is not limited to complaints via the Ohio Department of Insurance’s Consumer Complaint Form.  I am requesting this search in order to find complaints about providers demanding significant prepayment (i.e. more than the initial copay) for necessary, although not emergency, care and/or not providing a refund of the excess amount prepaid. I wish to receive the records in digital format.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Tracie McMillan

communications.subject: Ohio Department Of Insurance Public Records Request 5548
communications.communication:
Good afternoon.

I have been forwarded your public records request. In your request you have asked for records of complaints to the Department of Financial Services regarding insurance and/or health care providers from 2015 to 2025 containing any of the phrases "prepay," "upfront," "down payment," "refund," or "reimbursed," along with "prior to necessary medical care," and "non-emergency procedure" on file with the Department of Insurance.

Please be advised that you need to identify the specific record(s) that you seek and not specific information that is or may be contained in records. The Ohio Public Records Law does not require public offices to conduct research and find records that may contain information that may be of interest to a requester; State ex rel. Fant v. Tober (8th Dist. April 28, 1993) No. 63737, 1993 Ohio App. LEXIS 2591 at *4; aff'd 68 Ohio St. 3d 117 (1993); State ex rel. Thomas v. Ohio State University, 71 Ohio St. 3d 245 (1994). The Consumer Complaint Form does provide the complaint categories by which complaints are categorized.

The more detail you can provide to describe the complaints sought will allow ODI to create a more timely and accurate response. Providing detail such as specific complaint types, companies, agents, limited time frames.

Also,  the records retention period for complaints is two years post the closing of the complaint.

Please provide clarification of your request so that ODI may begin processing your request.

I look forward to you response so that we may be begin processing your request.

Please let me know if you have additional questions regarding public records requests.

Roger Hansen
Records Manager
Ohio Department of Insurance
6141-728-1384

communications.subject: RE: Ohio Open Records Law Request #5548
communications.communication:

I want to update my request to be for all consumer complaints related to (subject of the complaint) Elevance (formerly Anthem), Cigna, and UnitedHealth, where the category of the complaint is either “Prompt pay”, “premium refund,” or “payment not credited” from the time period of 2015 to 2025, (with the understanding that the records retention period for complaints is two years post the closing of the complaint.)

Please let me know if any further clarification is necessary.

Best,
Tracie McMillan

communications.subject: Final Response For Public Records Request
communications.communication:
Public Records Requests

Dear Tracie McMillan,

Your request for public records has been forwarded to my attention. In your request, you have asked for copies of public records of complaints to the Department of Financial Services regarding insurance and/or health care providers from 2015 to 2025 containing any of the phrases “prepay,” “upfront,” “down payment,” “refund,” or “reimbursed,” along with “prior to necessary medical care,” and “non-emergency procedure. on file with the Ohio Department of Insurance.

Pursuant to your request, please find the responsive records attached.

Social security numbers have been redacted pursuant to State ex rel. Beacon Journal Publishing Co. v. City of Akron, 70 Ohio St.3d 605 (1994).

Financial account and policy numbers have been withheld as these are considered non-records and do not meet the definition of “records” in R.C. 149.011 (G); State ex rel. Fant v. Enright, 66 Ohio St.3d 186, 188 (1993).

Please do not hesitate to contact the Department should you have any questions or need additional information.



Thank you,

Roger Hansen

Records Manager

Ohio Department of Insurance

50 W. Town Street, Suite 300

Columbus, OH 43215

(614)728-1384

title: First Amendment Trainings for Law-Enforcement Officers (Baltimore Police Department)

communications.subject: Maryland Public Information Act Request: First Amendment Trainings for Law-Enforcement Officers (Baltimore Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maryland Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. Any materials or programming (including handouts, slideshows, videos, textbooks, or other media) used in connection with providing training or guidance to law-enforcement officers in your agency with respect to any of the following subjects: (a) The First Amendment; (b) protests or demonstrations; (c) freedom of speech or expression; (d) filming police officers. This request is limited to materials used in trainings since January 1, 2020.

2. Any policy concerning whether trainings on the topics mentioned in (1) are mandatory, or regulating the frequency of such trainings.

3. A copy of any document sufficient to show the most recent training conducted for law-enforcement officers in your agency with respect to any of the subjects in (1). For example, this could be a receipt or contract for an outside vendor or speaker, or it could be a dated sign-in sheet from the training.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

For example, this could be a receipt or contract for an outside vendor or speaker, or it could be a dated sign-in sheet from the training.

The Maryland Public Information Act ("PIA"), Annotated Code of Maryland, General Provisions Article, § 4-101, et seq. governs your request.

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any and all materials, indices, directives, manuals, and other guiding documentation regarding the records generated and retained by California Highway Patrol, including but not limited to: 

• Record retention schedules
• Any other data structures used for the management of records: digital, paper, and otherwise

I request that you release records for this request on a rolling basis as they become available and in electronic form. If your agency does not maintain these public records, please let me know who does and include the proper custodian's name and address. If you choose to deny this request, please provide a written explanation for the denial including a reference to the specific statutory exemption(s) upon which you rely. communications.subject: Government Records Access and Management Act Request: Library Contract Request: Sage Journals
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Government Records Access and Management Act, I hereby request the following records:

The most recent contract, governing, base, or master license agreement with Sage relating to the licensing of Sage Journals;
All related terms and conditions, terms of service, amendments, addenda, appendices, attachments, product terms, MOUs, MOAs, data processing agreements, and/or letters of intent; and
All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to the contractual relations with Sage for journal licensing. 

Please do not limit your search to strictly direct agreements or renewals between the institution and the vendor (Sage), but include all agreements and related documentation through consortia such as the Utah Academic Library Consortium (UALC) or Lyrasis.

Responsive materials include all contracts, agreements, amendments, appendices, invoices, and any other documents listed above that incorporate language governing terms of use of Sage Journals.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ellen Dubinsky

There are three types of responsive information, and most records contain a combination.  First, available non-protected responsive records.  Second, information the Texas Attorney General previously determined confidential (see attached) and any information the Irving ISD determines is protected from disclosure by the Family Education Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA).  The Irving ISD will automatically redact this protected information prior to disclosure.  If your request only addresses these two types of information, as soon as practicable you will be contacted about the availability of the requested records (no records found or date of production and potential costs) and/or provided with copies of the records in question as redacted. A third type of responsive information may be covered by a discretionary exception to the PIA such as, but not limited to, attorney-client and/or attorney work product privileges.  The district is not allowed to automatically withhold or redact this information but must first seek a ruling from the Attorney General.  Such a petition shall be sent to the Attorney General and you within ten days of your request being received by the Irving ISD, but can ultimately delay the process since the Attorney General has 45 days to respond to the district’s request.  Therefore, we ask you to agree the Irving ISD may redact any attorney client, litigation, or attorney work product deemed necessary by law without seeking a ruling from the Attorney General. If your request is for student directory information, please note that our district policy FL(Local) only designates the student name, enrollment/withdraw dates, campus(es) attended, current grade level, and graduation status.  No other information will be released in compliance with FERPA; therefore, we will not produce the such information as student addresses or phone numbers.  If you have requested such information, we request that you please clarify/revise your request in compliance with our district policy. If at any time during this process you feel the Irving ISD has not responded in accordance with the PIA, you may contact the Texas Attorney General’s Hotline toll-free at (877) 673-6839 (877-OPENTEX) or in the Austin area at (512) 478-6736 (478-OPEN). You can monitor the progress of your request at the link below and will receive an email when your request has been completed. Again, thank you for using the Irving ISD Request Center. The Texas Public Information Act does not require a governmental body to create new information, to do legal research, or to answer questions. To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

- Any and all lists, spreadsheets or other organized datasets that detail potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States.
- Any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Moe Clark

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #2025-51
communications.communication:
Hi Ione,

Sorry for the confusion. Yes, for the second part of the list, I am looking forward to reviewing the discovery packets we discussed over the phone.

For the first part of the list, I'm hoping to review  "any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers." Basically, looking to review the documents that show the when/why an officer was placed on the Brady List. I understand this might not necessarily be the discovery packet since they aren't called as witnesses, but I'd like to be able to access why they were placed on the list in the first place. So any documentation kept by the Prosecutors Office on those officers. Feel free to give me a call if you have any other questions. 603-566-5210.

Thank you for your help!

Best,

Moe

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #2025-51
communications.communication:
Thanks for talking this through with me on the phone, Moe.  As we discussed, the materials that my office relied on to make the decision in determining whether to place an officer on a Brady list are considered work product and would not be released in response to a public disclosure request from our office.  However, those same records would not necessarily have the same protected status (or exemption from disclosure) in the hands of the agency from which they originated.

Based on our conversation, I understand that you are withdrawing the additional request that was made by email, below, for the records relied upon by my office in making a decision to place the officers of the top portion of our Brady list, but that you will be seeking those records directly from departments where those officers were employed.

-Ione

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

- All contracts, licenses, MOUs, MOAs, data agreements, letters of intent, State of Work documents, Scope of Work documents, and other agreement documents with Peregrine Technologies Inc. that were active any time between 1/1/2023 and 11/24/2024.
- All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to Peregrine Technologies Inc. communications.subject: [External Message Added] City of Los Angeles public records request #24-13089
communications.communication:
City of Los Angeles ************************************************************************ A message was sent to you regarding record request #24-13089: Dear Requester:   We reviewed your request for the following records regarding Peregrine Technologies Inc.:   *  All contracts, licenses, MOUs, MOAs, data agreements, letters of intent, State of Work documents, Scope of Work documents, and other agreement documents with Peregrine Technologies Inc. that were active any time between 1/1/2023 and 11/24/2024. * All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to Peregrine Technologies Inc. Responsive materials include all invoices, bills, receipts, check stubs, or any other records, including those possessed in an electronic format. Responsive materials include any records related to the funding of Peregrine Technologies Inc.-related technologies, partnerships, and subscriptions, including those related to civil asset forfeiture funds, grants, and any other funding sources. * A copy of all training materials, including but not limited to any handouts, workbooks, assessments, presentations, slides, videos, audio files, or other materials, either developed in-house or provided to the agency pertaining to the agency's use of Peregrine Technologies Inc. products. * A copy of all agency manuals either developed in-house or provided to the agency pertaining to the agency's use of Peregrine Technologies Inc. products. * A copy of all agency policies and procedures either developed in-house or provided to the agency pertaining to the agency's use of Peregrine Technologies Inc. products. * A roster of all agency employees who either have a user account for Peregrine Technologies Inc. products or have internal agency permissions to use Peregrine Technologies Inc. products as of 11/24/2024. * A roster of all agency employees who have completed agency training for the use of Peregrine Technologies Inc. products as of 11/24/2024.   Your request was made under the California Public Records Act (the Act). The Department is cognizant of its responsibilities under the Act. It recognizes the statutory scheme was enacted to maximize citizen access to the workings of government. The Act does not mandate disclosure of all documents within the government’s possession. Rather, by specific exemption and reference to other statutes, the Act recognizes that there are boundaries where the public’s right to access must be balanced against such weighty considerations as the right of privacy, a right of constitutional dimension under California Constitution, Article 1, Section 1. The law also exempts from disclosure records that are privileged or confidential or otherwise exempt under either express provisions of the Act or pursuant to applicable federal or state law, per California Government Code Sections 7927.200; 7927.700; 7923.600-7923.625; 7927.705; and 7922.000.   In regard to item 1, please visit the following website for records responsive to this portion of your request: https://cityclerk.lacity.org/lacityclerkconnect/index.cfm?fa=ccon.viewrecord&contractnum=C-145843   In regard to item 2, the Department has completed its review and is providing you with a record responsive to this portion of your request.   Please note that under Section 7920.530 of the CPRA, “public records” includes any writing containing information relating to the conduct of the public’s business and excludes writings containing or consisting of personal information unrelated to governmental activities. Similarly, Sections 7927.700 exempt records and/or information the disclosure of which would constitute an unwarranted invasion of personal privacy and/or would not serve the public interest. Therefore, responsive emails containing personal information (i.e., personal signatures and account numbers) are being provided to you with redactions.   In regard to items 3, 4, 6, and 7, please note that our office—the LAPD Public Records and Subpoena Response Section, CPRA Unit—does not house the records you are seeking. The Department is in the process of searching for the requested records. Please note that some of the records to be provided, if any, may be redacted pursuant to California Government Code Sections 7927.200; 7927.700; 7923.600-7923.625; 7927.705; and 7922.000. We will provide an update by January 24, 2025, and will notify you should anything change.   In regard to item 5, the Department has conducted a search based on the information provided and no responsive records were located.   If you have any questions, please respond to this email.   Respectfully,   LAPD Public Records & Subpoena Response Section, CPRA Unit ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at City of Los Angeles.

title: Cell Phone Service Provider/ Network Provider

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Cell Phone Service Provider/ Network Provider
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

I seek information on the cell phone and network provider for the City of Mount Vernon, New York. Additionally, I would appreciate it if you could provide me with the public cell phone numbers of all the members of the Building Department.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

George Johnston

MuckRock

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Cell Phone Service Provider/ Network Provider
communications.communication:
Thank you for your recent FOIL request.  It states in your email that “This is a follow up to a previous request..”  Please be advised, however, that this is the very first time that we received your request; we first received your request via e-mail on May 5 at 8:24PM.

Your request will be forwarded to the appropriate department (s) for a response. After the search has been performed the Law Department will contact you to inform you of the results of the search. It is the City’s goal to complete your request within 20 business days from its receipt. However, due to the number of requests being processed, your request might be completed beyond the date provided.

If responsive records are located, you will be notified and informed of the required payment, if any.  Advance payment is required in check or money order payable to the City of Mount Vernon before documents will be released.

Please be advised that duplicative requests, records already provided, and appeals previously answered, will not be considered.

If there are any questions or concerns with regard to the above, please feel free to contact this office.

Respectfully,
City of Mount Vernon – FOIL Team
[City-Seal-GoldMaroon-Small]

title: Department of Education Letters to 60 Universities and Colleges (University Of Hawaii, Manoa)

communications.subject: Hawaii Uniform Information Practices Act Request: Department of Education Letters to 60 Universities and Colleges (University Of Hawaii, Manoa)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Hawaii Uniform Information Practices Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of the letter sent to your institution by the United States Department of Education on or about March 10, 2025, referencing Title VI. The letter is referenced in this press release: https://www.ed.gov/about/news/press-release/us-department-of-educations-office-civil-rights-sends-letters-60-universities-under-investigation-antisemitic-discrimination-and-harassment.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Steinbaugh,

Please see the attached *Acknowledgment to Requester* form. In accordance
with the timeline for extenuating circumstances, we will provide our
written response by Wednesday, September 24, 2025.

Kindly direct all correspondence, questions, or comments regarding this
request to my attention moving forward.

Best regards,
Elmer Kaʻai

University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Mount Vernon/ Police Records
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

A list of all personnel employed by the Mount Vernon Police Department including their rank, pay grade, and salary.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

George Johnston

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Thomas Henschel interaction reports
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Regarding an interaction with Thomas Henschel on 01/25/2013:
- All incident, dispatch log entries and arrest reports. Incident reports and case records refer to reports produced with notes and narratives, a description of what happened by the responding officer, trace reports, case notes and litigation files
- All unedited body-worn camera / bodycam recordings. I am specifically requesting the unedited body-worn camera recordings captured by all officers present for the full duration of the incident, including audio recordings associated with the footage. If any portion of the requested footage must be redacted, I ask that you clearly indicate the portions that have been redacted and provide an explanation of the legal basis for the redactions
- All 911 or calls for service logs, audio and transcripts
- All computer aided dispatch (CAD) reports and a copy of your department’s dispatch 10 signals/codes, agency dispatch signals/codes and CAD signals/codes

I request these records in their native digital formats and not in formats that degrade the accessibility of the records, such as tabular data converted to PDF or Word files. If converting the native digital format to another high-fidelity format, such as CSV or Excel, please take care not to introduce formatting inconsistencies or errors, which can occur in the conversion process (for example, encoding errors or the inclusion of internal unescaped quotation marks in CSV files). Should the records above represent certain values as numeric codes or abbreviations that are not self-explanatory, I additionally request all records necessary to interpret those codes and abbreviations.

I am a member of the news media. The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

Production of Responsive Records on a Rolling Basis: In the event that a portion of the present request is completed before the full request is completed, I ask that the records be produced on a rolling basis.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Sarah Hopkins
